    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-06-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-06-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="166"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d166">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">761.6711/6–1845</note>
                <head>No. 166 <lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">British Embassy</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract]<note n="1" xml:id="d166fn1">For the full text
                            of this memorandum, see <ref target="#d688">document No.
                            688</ref>.</note>
                    </seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Memorandum</hi>
                </p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
                <p>In accordance with the understanding reached at Yalta,<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d166fn2">See <ref target="frus1945Berlinv02#d1416">vol. <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">ii</hi>, document No. 1416, section <hi
                                rend="smallcaps">xiv</hi>
                        </ref>.</note> this Government stands ready to discuss the question of the
                    [Turkish] Straits at the forthcoming meeting of the Heads of Government when,
                    presumably, the Soviet Government will present its desiderata in this
                    connection. So far as the Department can ascertain, the conversation between Mr.
                        <persName corresp="#p_MVM1">Molotov</persName> and the Turkish
                        Ambassador<note n="3" xml:id="d166fn3">
                        <persName corresp="#p_SS2">Selim Sarper</persName>. For an account of the
                        conversation referred to, see <ref target="#d684">document No.
                        684</ref>.</note> took place in a friendly atmosphere and was of an
                    exploratory character. If this is the case, the Department considers it
                    premature to protest what amounts to a preliminary exchange of views. …</p>
                <p>… In any case, this Government would not wish to appear as having reached any
                    decision on this question prior to the Heads of Government meeting.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GJC1">J[<hi rend="smallcaps">oseph</hi>] C G[<hi
                                rend="smallcaps">rew</hi>]</persName>
                    </signed>
                    <dateline rendition="#left">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-06-23">June 23,
                            1945</date>.</dateline>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
